                            true 1P pitch. A surface you could plug into.
                        </p>
                    </div>
                    <div class="motif">
                        <div class="motif__demo">
                            <span
                                class="jumper"
                                style="--fam: var(--fam-ctl); width:100%;"
                                aria-hidden="true"><i></i><i></i></span
                            >
                        </div><h4>The jumper</h4><p>
                            A colored wire arc connecting two points — section dividers, link
                            underlines, "see also" pointers. Always lands on a square endpoint.
                        </p>
                    </div>
                    <div class="motif">
                        <div class="motif__demo">
                            <span class="mono m-ruler"
                                >1&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;5&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;10&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;15&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;20&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;25</span
                            >
                        </div><h4>The ruler</h4><p>
                            Breadboard column numbers as marginalia — page headers, progress
                            indicators, timeline scales. Counting holes, everywhere.
                        </p>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
        </section>

        <!-- ========== 12 EVOLUTION ========== -->
        <section id="evolution" class="ds-sec ds-sec--paper">
            <div class="container">
                <header class="ds-head">
                    <Plate fill="12" rest="EVOLUTION" />
                    <span class="label muted">How the system grows</span>
                </header>
                <h2>Growing the ecosystem</h2>
                <p class="ds-intro">
                    Naming: keep the "___ Buddy" friendly layer, and back it with a systematic
                    designator — BS-FAMILY-NUMBER — that lives in mono on every card, doc, and URL.
                    The registry below is the single source of truth.
                </p>

                <table class="reg-table">
                    <thead
                        ><tr
                            ><th>Designator</th><th>Friendly name</th><th>Family</th><th>Status</th
                            ></tr
                        ></thead
                    >
                    <tbody>
                        {
                            registry.map((r) => (
                                <tr>
                                    <td class="mono">{r.id}</td>
                                    <td>{r.name}</td>
                                    <td>
                                        <span class="chip" style={`--fam: var(--fam-${r.fam});`}>
                                            {r.label}
                                        </span>
                                    </td>
                                    <td class="mono">{r.status}</td>
                                </tr>
                            ))
                        }
                    </tbody>
                </table>

                <div class="rules">
                    <div class="rule">
                        <h4>Hues are scarce</h4><p>
                            Six families is the ceiling. A new card must join an existing family
                            before anyone proposes a seventh hue — scarcity is what keeps the color
                            code legible.
                        </p>
                    </div>
                    <div class="rule">
                        <h4>Copper for community</h4><p>
                            Third-party and community cards use the copper keybar and a BS-X-
                            designator. Adoption into an official family is an event — the card
                            literally earns its color.
                        </p>
                    </div>
                    <div class="rule">
                        <h4>Tokens ship with hardware</h4><p>
                            Design tokens are versioned with board revisions (REV A, B, C…). When
                            the silkscreen changes, the website changes from the same commit. One
                            registry, one truth.
                        </p>
                    </div>
                    <div class="rule">
                        <h4>New surfaces, old motifs</h4><p>
                            Apps, videos, merch, trade-show booths: start with the plate, keybar,
                            rails, and dot field before inventing anything new. If two motifs are
                            present, it's already on-brand.
                        </p>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
        </section>
    </div>
</BaseLayout>

